This is how history is manipulated and used by your masters when you don't
guard your own.  
History has always been monopolised by those agencies in power. It has been
dictated and made to be accepted. When knowledge is subjected to such
monopoly, it doesnt stay away from the power politics of distorting history
for their own benefits and convenience. When your time dimension is let to be
manipulated,distorted and misinterpreted, the space you exist will be
distorted. And the space doesn't necessarily mean your geographical space, but
also your economic, social and political space. This beautifully serves the
master to swing the politics towards his gain.  
In Manipur, we see distortions every where. And the recent being the one where
attempts were made to distort the history of Pangals by some agents who have
established their positions accepted in the society championing the cause for
"Undivided Manipur" \- a cause that surely attracts hearts of many but hollow
to its bone.  
When you talk about undivided Manipur, what sort of undivided Manipur you are
visioning. Is it the same unequal, highly skewed space to serve the status
quo? Or is it otherwise?  
~ Himat Tampakmayum

I would like to make a point regarding the genesis of the word "Pangal". This
is my opinion based on facts, common sense and logic. Bengalis (irrespective
of religion) are basically divided into two "groups" ie: Bengalis from West
Bengal and those from present day Bangladesh. The WB Bengalis are called
"ghotis" while that from Bangladesh are called "bongals". This grouping is
purely based on their geographical location. When the Bongal Muslims (mostly
from Sylhet) came to Manipur in the 1500s and 1600s, they were called as
Pangals as the Meiteis could not pronounce the word "bongals" properly. And
this became the byword as the word "pangal"/strength is in the Meitei lexicon.
By this reasoning, Shanti Das Gosain (who was from Sylhet and a Hindu) is also
a Pangal/Bongal who came in 1700s.

Blinded by false pride, the majority community refuses to acknowledge the
existence of Article 371(C) of our Constitution for the last several decades.
Manipur Land Revenue and Land Reforms Act 1960, coupled with Hill Area
Committee divided the hill and valley people drawing a clear line of
demarcation in all respects. Even the Yelhoumee (original inhabitants) status
is divided. While the one is officially recognised, the other is unofficial
and looks like self styled Yelhoumee. We should call a spade a spade. Article
342(1) made all this division and unless the social disparity among the
original inhabitants is removed by a Constitutional amendment -- either
majority community becoming ST or ST friends general -- the status quo will
remain always, with Meitei at the receiving end forever. At this rate, the
geopolitical reality demands a collective political wisdom devoid of quixotic
pipe dreams.
